Subsidy Traps
Cambridge, USA—No policy pits good economics so directly against good politics as do subsidies for food and energy.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the core issue faced by the three most important new leaders of the world. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President "Jokowi" Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Sisi's need to cut subsidies is turning out to be better than expected.
On the contrary, Modi is facing a worse situation than anticipated, which could even undermine the long-awaited WTO agreement.
The situation facing Jokowi remains unclear.
In July, Sisi accomplished something rare for a leader in North Africa and the Middle East: he significantly cut long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
Strangely, there were almost no protests against this.
Egypt's food subsidy program, which costs over $5 billion annually, also urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained so low that they are often used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to reduce such subsidies often led to unrest, and even the overthrow of governments.
But the Tunisian government seems to be making progress in this area as well.
Bread subsidies have been cut by 13%.
Tunisia has no choice.
Even after the subsidy cuts, the current government's target for the budget deficit for the next fiscal year still reached 10% of GDP (14% without the subsidy cuts).
However, almost no one anticipated that Xi, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, would act more swiftly than Modi. Modi secured the prime minister's position through an overwhelming democratic majority in India, where there is an urgent desire for comprehensive economic reforms.
In Indonesia, Jokowi, who began governing in October, inherited long-standing fuel subsidies amounting to as much as $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government spending), which had already burdened the country.
The outgoing Susilo had already taken a brave first step a year earlier by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors recommended cutting the remaining subsidies, and he also openly stated his plan to implement the cuts gradually over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies because agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfect competitive fields, the government — not large private monopolies — is the root cause.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
Food and fossil fuel subsidies have sparked sharp controversies because they are often implemented under the banners of environmental protection or equality, but they are actually ineffective for these goals and often have the opposite effect.
Only less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Gasoline subsidies in most countries benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies go to the poorest people, while 52.6% flow into the pockets of the richest.
Worldwide, far less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, as evidenced by Modi's government, which aims to protect agricultural subsidies in India.
Indeed, the Modi government rejected WTO compromises, undoing the most important progress in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in poor countries; while at other times they benefit producers at the expense of consumers, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to have both.
As a result, India has accomplished a feat: supplying wheat to consumers at artificially low prices, while at the same time experiencing oversupply because farmers can get high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies through agricultural inputs — electricity, water, and fertilizers — while the environment is being destroyed.
) The government has acquired large amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, while the small portion distributed to consumers is both corrupt and does not meet the goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and purchase reserves.
But it knows that this would violate World Trade Organization rules.
Since it is impossible to permanently change these rules, Modi simply rejected the trade facilitation agreement that the WTO was so eager to have.
Once subsidies are implemented, it is hard to retract them.
When world commodity prices rise (as they did over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot shield them from the impact.
But people accustomed to government-set food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a very strong reason not to implement subsidies from the outset.
However, this does not mean that maintaining subsidies is necessarily the best choice for shrewd politicians once they are in place.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents could also erupt.
Similarly, if the growing gap eventually leads to a sharper rise in retail prices, slow-moving leaders will also not benefit.
In an ideal scenario, while reducing subsidies for food and energy, other more efficient measures to support low-income groups should be implemented.
Developing countries have gained considerable experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as conditional cash transfer programs like Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification system.
However, some countries are forced to make adjustments only when a budget crisis hits, and they may not have the funds available for transfers to alleviate the pain.
Smart politicians might implement unpopular adjustments right from the start of their tenure.
Both Jokowi and Xi have adopted this approach.
Modi, who had won a landslide victory in the elections with the slogan of market reforms, has now fallen behind.
